  "prompt": "In outer space how do rockets move if there environment is a vacuum?",
  "response": "In outer space, rockets move by using Newton's Third Law of Motion: \"For every action, there is an equal and opposite reaction.\" Here's how it works:\n\n1. Rocket Propulsion:\n- Rockets carry fuel and oxidizer (oxygen)\n- When these are mixed and burned in the rocket engine, they create hot, high-pressure gases\n- These gases are forcefully ejected out of the rocket's rear nozzle at extremely high speeds\n\n2. Reaction Principle:\n- As the gases are pushed backward out of the rocket (action), the rocket is simultaneously pushed forward (reaction)\n- This works in a vacuum because the rocket doesn't need external air or surface to push against\n- The rocket's engines provide the thrust by expelling mass in one direction\n\n3. Conservation of Momentum:\n- The rocket moves in the opposite direction of the expelled gases\n- The faster and more mass ejected, the greater the rocket's acceleration\n\n4. No Air Resistance:\n- In space, without atmospheric friction, the rocket continues moving in the direction of thrust\n- Once a rocket is in motion, it will keep moving unless another force acts upon it\n\nThis principle allows spacecraft to maneuver and change direction in the vacuum of space by firing engines in specific directions.",
